# The display Property

The `display` property is the most fundamental layout tool in CSS. It controls how an element participates in the document flow.

## Core display Values

| Value | Behaviour |
|---|---|
| `block` | Full width, starts a new line — `div`, `p`, `h1`–`h6`, `section` |
| `inline` | Flows with text, ignores width/height — `span`, `a`, `em`, `strong` |
| `inline-block` | Flows with text but accepts width/height and box properties |
| `none` | Element is completely removed from layout and invisible |
| `flex` | Creates a flex container (covered next lesson) |
| `grid` | Creates a grid container |

## The position Property

`position` controls where an element is placed relative to its normal location or a parent:

| Value | How it works |
|---|---|
| `static` | Default — follows normal document flow |
| `relative` | Offset from its normal position using top/right/bottom/left |
| `absolute` | Removed from flow; positioned relative to nearest positioned ancestor |
| `fixed` | Removed from flow; always stays in the same viewport position |
| `sticky` | Scrolls normally, then sticks to the viewport when reaching a threshold |

```css
/* Relative — shifts 20px down from its normal position */
.badge {
  position: relative;
  top: 20px;
}

/* Absolute — top-right corner of its positioned parent */
.tooltip {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  right: 0;
}

/* Fixed — always visible in the bottom-right corner */
.chat-button {
  position: fixed;
  bottom: 24px;
  right: 24px;
}
```

## Positioned Ancestor

For `position: absolute` to work predictably, the parent element must have `position: relative` (or absolute/fixed/sticky). If no positioned ancestor exists, the element positions itself relative to the `<body>`.

## overflow Property

```css
.container {
  overflow: hidden;   /* clips content that extends beyond bounds */
  overflow: scroll;   /* always shows scrollbars */
  overflow: auto;     /* shows scrollbars only when needed */
  overflow-x: hidden; /* hide only horizontal overflow */
}
```

## z-index — Stacking Order

Positioned elements (not `static`) stack on top of each other. Higher `z-index` values appear in front:

```css
.overlay { position: fixed; z-index: 100; } /* in front */
.content { position: relative; z-index: 1;  } /* behind */
```

